Immigration enforcement became the main instrument for this expansion of power. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem and Miller ordered immigration agents to triple daily arrests to 3,000 people per day, turning enforcement into a quota system. That target could not be met without sweeping up people in courthouses and workplaces, and it encouraged agents to treat volume as success, not accuracy. The human consequences were visible in the wrongful detention of a U.S. citizen, Leonardo Garcia Venegas, whose Real ID was dismissed as fake while he filmed an ICE raid, and in the wrongful arrest of an undocumented college student in Georgia under a 287(g) agreement that deputized local police as immigration agents. At the same time, the administration revoked humanitarian parole for a critically ill four\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old Mexican girl whose life depended on care in California. These were not isolated errors. They were the predictable results of a system that treats migrants\'97and sometimes citizens who resemble them\'97as numbers to be hit, not rights\u8209 bearing persons.\
