The same pattern of pressure and pushback appeared in media and information. The White House stopped publishing and removed official transcripts of Trump\'92s speeches from its public database, leaving only a limited set of videos. That decision narrowed the documentary record of presidential communications, making it harder for journalists, scholars, and citizens to search, quote, and hold the president to his own words. At the same time, the administration issued an executive order cutting off congressionally appropriated funds to NPR and PBS, accusing them of bias and propaganda. NPR, three Colorado public radio stations, and PBS responded with lawsuits, arguing that the order violated the First Amendment and usurped Congress\'92s power of the purse. A separate federal judge ordered the administration to release more than $12 million in previously allocated funding to Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, reinforcing that appropriated funds cannot be withheld as a tool of political retaliation. Yet the broader trend was clear. Independent public media were being starved, while loyal outlets were rewarded, and the president himself posted a QAnon\uc0\u8209 linked meme casting himself as \'93on a mission from God\'94 after courts ruled against his tariffs, using conspiracy imagery to delegitimize judicial checks.\
